INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (59,148,'Brant Day','artistdude08@gmail.com','','204.62.150.2','2013-05-29 18:13:00','2013-05-29 18:13:00','Having a portfolio to start out with is most likely a must for all upcoming designers. Even Folio requires you to share some sort of \"profile of work\" (see attached image) whether from a website, dribbble, or behance page to even get into the website. Obviously there is need to showcase your skills and abilities at some points more than others. I would encourage everyone to maintain some sort of portfolio no matter what. You\'re just like any other company or agency, people will want to research you despite having met you. Whenever I send out emails or begin new projects gaurenteed I see that person has looked at my linkedin profile or is now following me on dribbble etc. They are avenues of connection and discovery, I can\'t imagine it would actually hold you back from success. I would imagine that higher level clients would require a portfolio so as to be sure of their investment.\n\n\n\nI say that but I am not working full-time freelance so my experience is NOT your experience nor do I disagree with the the point that you are making. Basically to go out and hit the pavement and just start talking and making contacts. That process is much easier if you have a body of work which you can rely on, including process and experience from which you can pull.\n\n\nAs you put it though this is your experience and you are merely putting it out there for this very purpose, discussion, and to help others generate ideas and get started on their own. I hate playing the middle ground here but I don\'t disagree or agree completely either way. Things will work for some and fail for others.',0,'0','Disqus/1.1(2.74):912943364','',0,0);
