INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (45,2,'2013-04-02 00:06:57','2013-04-02 00:06:57','Designers don\'t like to think of themselves as marketers. Writing copy and crafting websites that are specifically-designed-to-sell is often considered sleezy. This is hurting the design industry.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nMost of the design industry focuses on things like user interfaces and user experience to provide value to our clients. I know because I\'ve identified myself as a designer for the past 5 years. It\'s understandable rationale, you always want to create an awesome product that is downright beautiful and intuitive.\r\n\r\nThink about the design portfolios you see on dribbble and around the web. They\'re sleek, intuitive, beautiful.... and they all sorta look the same. They don\'t tell you how they helped solve a problem, they just show you the hi-res designs of their solutions. What if you\'re competing against 15 other awesomely-designed startups (which you probably are)?\r\n\r\nThat\'s a problem designers don\'t ever answer because they\'re too busy writing headlines on their website like \"less is more\", \"show don\'t tell\", and (insert supposed Steve Jobs quote here).\r\n\r\nHowever, putting the focus on design before selling your product is a huge disservice to your company and here\'s 10 reasons why:\r\n\r\n<strong>1. It\'s a myth that a great experience sells itself.</strong>\r\n\r\nI\'m all for creating a product that is a joy to use, the simple fact is that unless you can market the product to get enough revenue and traffic, you\'re just wasting everyones time on a massive failure. Think about it, how many times have you built something awesome only to watch it go down in flames because \'Build it and they will come\' is total bs.\r\n\r\nThe average website <a href=\"http://spinnakr.com/blog/ideas/2012/08/how-to-calculate-the-roi-of-conversion-rate-optimization/\">conversion rate is 1-2%</a>, meaning you need 10,000 visitors in order to get 200 conversions, if you\'re lucky.\r\n\r\nYou\'re not gonna get 10,000 visitors just because your design is exquisite. In my experience, the design community (dribbble and twitter in particular) can muster a good  2-3k hits if they like your design and decide to share it with their followers (which usually means they\'re sending other designers your way looking to check out your sweet design nectar). However, unless your product is specifically targeting designers, there\'s not a lot of use having designers visit your site.\r\n\r\nOther then that, the average person is going to need more then an awesome design to share your site nowadays... maybe because startups are focusing so much on awesome branding, it\'s almost expected.\r\n\r\n<strong>2. A great home or landing page design should come only after extensive research and getting inside the head of your customers... crafting good copywriting makes you understand your product, and more importantly your customers.</strong>\r\n\r\nWe\'ve all seen lorem ipsum on rough design concepts... (I\'ve even been guilty of it too). However, why the hell would you start designing intricate details without any clue as to the message your trying to convey? The messaging should be dictating these design decisions, or at least guiding them.\r\n\r\nYou can\'t tailor the goal of a website to fit the design, that\'s just moronic.\r\n\r\nDesigners just end up putting startups in a box when they use lorem ipsum, or placeholder text, literally.\r\n\r\nSo why do designers feel the need to make constraints to something as important as the message of a website? It\'s because they haven\'t spent the time and hard work to deeply understand the purpose of the website and the people that will be visiting it. Your left having to fit this incredibly important message into a predetermined area, which may not even be the right fit for it. This leads to...\r\n\r\n<strong>3. This horrible, headline startups keep repeating over and over:</strong>\r\n\r\n<span class=\"highlight\">Finally, a product that saves you time and money.</span>\r\n\r\nOr it\'s equally lazy cousin,\r\n\r\n<span class=\"highlight\">The faster/easier/better way to blah blah.</span>\r\n\r\nWhen I see these headlines I close my window and proceed to punch myself in the face. Don\'t tell me that you\'re better, at least tell me how you\'re better damnit.\r\n\r\nIf you don\'t even care enough about helping me understand what your product does in one sentence, then why should I buy it. This is going to be a bad relationship --- and I hate you.\r\n\r\n<strong>4. Optimizing your headline - is probably the easiest quick-win your startup can make...</strong>\r\n\r\nAnd it\'s simply because everyone else is just so terrible. If your headline is simply not-horrible, like the headlines above, then you have a huge advantage...\r\n\r\nFinding those headlines (at the top of this blog post) literally took 2 minutes on dribbble, they\'re everywhere!!!!\r\n\r\nWhen you finally visit a website that has clear and concise copy, it doesn\'t even feel like they\'re marketing to you. It feels like a friend is telling you to check out something awesome. They show you the respect and understanding you and your problem deserve and so your brain instantly goes to \'give them your freakin money already\' mode.\r\n\r\nThat’s why a resource like <a href=\"http://www.copyhackers.com/\">Joanne Weibe\'s Copyhackers</a> is so great (go there and buy her books). It helps you understand how to craft a message that will feel like you know the person you’re talking to, because you will know the person you\'re talking to.\r\n\r\nAnd yet, by in large the design community totally skips this fact in favor of pretty shiny graphics or (insert latest trend here... is it still flat design?).\r\n\r\n<strong>5. Designers should be copywriters anyway.</strong>\r\n\r\nAnd if you\'re a designer reading this, have no fear (and there will be more help for you below) because Startups are kinda stuck with you... because it seems good copywriters are hard as heck to find.\r\n\r\nAnyways, a better solution then finding a copywriter and designer who mix well together is to find a designer who puts a huge emphasis on writing great copy before designing (or at making sure the copy is already masterfully written). That\'s the test for finding a good designer, it\'s pass or fail.\r\n\r\nIt\'s fun to design copy and you get to charge more by providing much more value, so it\'s a win-win for designers and their clients.\r\n\r\nAs an industry, design isn\'t really the product we\'re selling, we\'re selling more revenue for the companies we work with. It\'s a gain in the finance department. Until we address that and make it a core fabric of our industry, designers will continue to feel like a \'pixel pusher\' or production designer  --- aka a mindless, soulless, yes-man.\r\n\r\n<strong>6. Designers don\'t like to think of themselves as marketers, making them unable to solve your marketing needs.</strong>\r\n\r\nDesigners like to think they\'re saving the world in some small way when they create \"pixel perfection\" (or as I refer to it; spending a bunch of time on stuff nobody fucking cares about). When was the last time a copywriter had that kind of attitude? Never, because when you\'re writing copy you know you\'re not saving the world because you have a clear goal; usually sell the shit out of this product.\r\n\r\nA perfect example of designers wanting pixel perfection is the common notion that designers must emulate Apple. Not so much in looks usually, but in the fact that everything about the company must be perfectly designed. For every problem just throw design or more branding at it. That\'s crazy talk, especially when it comes to tech startups where branding is of minimal significance...\r\n\r\nHave you seen some of the atrocious 1.0 versions of your favorite websites like twitter and facebook? Have you seen 37signals\' websites? They\'re bare minimum, and they started out as a design agency! Often times the design of superficial elements just doesn\'t matter enough to invest that kind of time into.\r\n\r\n<strong>7. A designer is only valuable if he helps you sell your product, everything else is fluff. </strong>\r\n\r\nThe need to combat this fact is why designers also have a reputation for being hard to work with. Their tendency to spend endless amounts of time focusing on insignificant details... to the chagrin of the team around them.\r\n\r\nDevelopers, entrepreneurs, and various other people in the tech industry have all stepped out and said designers can be egotistical and stall productivity with their desires to focus solely on design - as if it were the most important aspect of the business.\r\n\r\nFor example, a designer might spend 4 hours on making sure a minor user interface detail is juuuust right. However, this detail may have little to no effect on the user\'s experience or that businesses\' bottom line.\r\n\r\nFocusing on fluff is a bad use of everyones time, and especially a startup or small business.\r\n\r\nThe fact is, we\'re not designing for designers. People visiting your website will most likely not have the same attention to detail. If they do, they might not even mind.\r\n\r\nThey <strong>will</strong> mind not knowing what the hell is different about your product.\r\n\r\n<strong>8. No one cares about design, you only care about the benefits of good design (ie. making money and having a better product).</strong>\r\n\r\nA great example of how designers fail to realize what\'s most important is crowd-sourcing, the anti-christ of the design community.\r\n\r\nBasically, designers claim crowd-sourcing is everything that\'s wrong with the world because it kills decent jobs for designers by offering design at such a cheap price that we simply can\'t compete.\r\n\r\nTotal BS. Educating people on what design is --- is usually one of the biggest barriers in working with clients!\r\n\r\nTheir argument that taking work away from real designers who charge appropriate rates for their work is false because the people who are looking for a $100 dollar logo aren’t the same people who are looking to hire a freelance designer (and much less a design agency).\r\n\r\nIt’s a completely different group of people. In fact, crowdsourcing is actually EXPANDING the amount of people out there who are becoming familiar with design.\r\n\r\nIt’s true that the quality level of these designs are nowhere near what you would get if you hired a real designer at a proper rate but that doesn\'t matter to a startup.\r\n\r\nSaying that a $100 logo is taking work away from you is saying your logos are worth $100.\r\n\r\nSaying people shouldn’t accept anything less than pixel perfection is saying you care more about design then your clients business.\r\n\r\n<strong>9. Without a goal or a message, great design can\'t exist because it becomes art.</strong>\r\n\r\nThe reason a great line of copy feels like they\'re reading your mind is because the writer has actually taken the time to research and get to know the person they\'re talking to. When you don\'t know that person you have a superficial looking website that may look right but has nothing to offer.\r\n\r\nThe last time you felt excited about a project, I bet it wasn\'t because they told you it would save you time or money.\r\n\r\nInstead they probably showed you exactly how it would make your life easier (possibly by saving you time or money).\r\n\r\n<strong>10. If a design isn\'t presenting a message then it\'s not winning you more customers. Plain and simple.</strong>\r\n\r\nThink about the nazi flag. If you had no clue about Nazi history, you might pick up that flag and say, \"Nice looking flag.\"\r\n\r\nHowever because you know the story behind that flag and everything it stands for you don\'t have this reaction. The design of the flag matters so little to how you feel about it, that it could literally be any flag in the world. All that matters is the story behind it.\r\n\r\nYou need to craft the right story for your startup, and people who know how to write copy are the ones who will help you do it.\r\n\r\n<strong>So how do you create a message that will sell your product and create recurring revenue?</strong>\r\n\r\nOf course, there were some generalizations about designers and copywriters throughout this post. Not all copywriters are awesome and not all designers only care about stupid details. The answer for your startup is going to vary.\r\n\r\nYou can swear off designers and hire only copywriters instead (you know because I hate making money). Or you can instead hire a designer that can quickly and easily explain his copywriting system.\r\n\r\nHere\'s three quick methods for extracting copy that will resonate with your visitor. It\'s the same whether you\'re a designer, copywriter, startup founder, or bootstrapper:\r\n\r\n1. Go to amazon.com and take a look at reviews of books or products that your customer might be reading. Open an excel file and write down some of the words they use when explaining why they loved/hated a product. Try incorporating some of these specific words in your headline.\r\n\r\n2. Go to great blog posts around the web that your potential customers might be reading about the service or type of service you offer. Write down the headlines and how many tweets, likes, and comments those blog posts have. Use key phrases or words from the most popular blog post titles.\r\n\r\n3. Go to your competitions website\'s and put all of their headlines into one excel file. Now, using the first 2 steps above craft a headline that none of these websites could apply to their website, because it mentions the unique value that you offer.\r\n\r\nThere\'s enough fluff out there, to cut through it all - your startup needs to be crystal-clear with its messaging. As a designer, and member/student of design - I\'ve found that good copywriting is going to make all the difference for early startups, and design can sometimes be overrated.','Good Copy Is More Valuable than Design','','publish','closed','closed','','warning-startups-need-good-copy-more-then-design','','\nhttp://spinnakr.com/blog/ideas/2012/08/how-to-calculate-the-roi-of-conversion-rate-optimization/','2014-04-25 04:54:00','2014-04-25 04:54:00','',0,'http://robertwilliams.wpengine.com/?p=45',0,'post','',0,NULL);
