INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (80,2,'2013-04-03 17:21:49','2013-04-03 17:21:49','Sam Adoqeui\'s books; How Successful Artists Study, and Origin of Inspiration served as the basis for my study\'s as an art student. I had a chance to interview Sam and ask him a few questions regarding his work.\r\n\r\n<em>This interview was originally sent to <a href=\"http://www.startupdesignnewsletter.com\">my newsletter</a>, signup to get access first.</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>1. In an age where instant critique and feedback is so prevalent in art and design, especially online, how do we make sure exhibiting our work publicly will truly be in our own best interest?</strong>\r\n\r\nSometimes up and coming artists rush too quickly to expose their work publicly, as if they are yearning for praises and therapeutic feedbacks instead of constructive criticism. This makes it very difficult for any sincere experienced or professional artist to give objective criticism. Imagine if you have 100 likes on facebook and Sam Adoquei have 2 likes then Sam Adoqeui sticks his head out to make any comments or suggestion?\r\n\r\nConstructive criticism is as important to the giver as it is to the receiver. And an important assert for growth. If you really want constructive criticism then be sincere, honest and respectful on how you ask for it. The art of creating great art in most ways has objective principles that could be taught and mastered if presented by an experienced artist.\r\n\r\n<strong>2. In your experience, what has been the best technique for calming the urge to criticize or refuse artworks that you are not naturally drawn to and instead still extract knowledge from them?</strong>\r\n\r\nLuckily I am blessed to have respect for all the traditions, because of this, I find something great out of artworks I don’t like to criticize then concentrate on talking about the good things about the work without criticizing it. On the other hand if I like the artist, then I feel a bit guilty for not being honest, in this case I go on by giving some honest and sincere suggestions in addition to the praises.\r\n\r\n<strong> 3. How can an artist or designer tailor their career to accommodate the ways that the three types of buyers of art buy what they buy? (Based on the three types of buyers outlined in the book: the buyer who works and lives off his income, the buyer buying for someone else with unlimited funds, and the buyer who is concerned with what everyone else will think)</strong>\r\n\r\nFirst and foremost artists have to psychological see themselves as professionals who have to make a living in order to create as they wish. Only after this mental acceptance or realization that artists can create different artworks for different clienteles and not worry what others say. Young artists of today wrap themselves too much in the romantic idea of becoming an artist. in doing so they never prepare well for the real world awaiting. The fear of thinking going commercial is a bad thing hinders all potentials artists. The idealistic and romantic approaches to art deceive the young about the realistic becoming a true artist.\r\n\r\nGreatness is not limited by being realistic about making a living. Whenever greatness fails to reach its fullest potentials it is because the artist could not back\r\n\r\n<strong> 4. As creative people we tend to define ourselves by what we do, but when I look at my biggest heroes, especially in music, I see an uncompromising attitude toward their art. I don\'t feel as though my commercial design work, created for others, always has the same uncompromising attitude. In order to give society my full true vision, is it skill, technique, or something else I need to improve?</strong>\r\n\r\nIt is always best to cultivate one’s vision. Vision is everything; vision makes the artists stand out from others, cultivated vision is our contribution to humanity. Skill and technique are just part of the tools in ones toolbox, they make ideas easy to execute. Skill and technique are tools when assisted by knowledge and experience help bring artists ideas to life as he/she envisioned. Skill and technique don’t make greatness, vision and ideas do. The artist’s voice is his/her unique vision. Sometimes playing safe, not trying hard enough to cultivate ones vision or rushing to get things done, force the artist to quick results that do not represent his/her vision. Being inspired by and extracting ideas from that which you love most are the keys to finding your uniqueness and standing out from others, The following is a short excerpt from my small book ”Origin of Inspiration” Essay four “Finding Your Vision”.\r\n<blockquote>Finding Your Vision\r\n\r\n(Excerpt from “Origin of Inspiration “Essay Four page 39 there is more explanation in the book)\r\n\r\nThe fifth attribute an artist needs in order to be able to accomplish great things is vision. To attain vision, we need the other four qualities (inspiration, passion, talent and skill). Our vision is what makes us unique and special. Literally, vision means an artist’s unique way of seeing the world, the special and specific choices the artist makes when observing the world around him. It is also what the artist imagines and sees with his unique mind’s eye and brings out by way of his art. Vision is like a lighthouse, it guides the artist to a specific area of nature or life or to a subject that is personal to the artist, one that others might have overlooked. Vision also includes that which the artist’s conscience tells him the world ought to be—or what the world is lacking. Vision is that unique and special contribution we bring and add to life; it is that which no one can provide but us. Passion, inspiration, talent and skill all have to come together so that our vision can be achieved. Two artists standing in front of a landscape scene, a still life subject or a figure in its surroundings, will find inspiration from different parts of the same subject. In a landscape, one artist might choose to paint a view that emphasizes the sky while the other will focus on the vegetation. Vision is what makes life meaningful. The uniqueness and importance of a vision is what makes one artist or scientist’s legacy endure more than that of others.\r\n\r\n“The influence of each human being on others in this life is a kind of immortality.” — John Quincy Adams\r\n\r\nSome aspects of vision can be explained but not all; for example, an entrepreneur can explain what he wants to bring to a certain culture. An artist can sometimes explain his ambitions and intentions. But not everything. When Marconi explained that he envisioned sound coming out of wires, he was put in an asylum because he was thought to be going mad. He eventually went on to invent the radio. Leonardo da Vinci faced his own problems with authority when he decided that by dissecting cadavers he would better understand the human machine in order to pursue his vision. In recent years, because of Modern Art (which says that anything goes and everything is art—and if I call myself an artist, therefore I am one), it has become common to have skills and style but no vision, or to have vision but no technical skills. An artist can also have skills and vision, but no style. Of these three essential qualities (skill, style and vision) that serve as the backbone for successful artists, style is the only element an artist can do without, but luckily style comes without the artist making too much effort. Technical skills and vision when improved upon make the pursuit of art very easy and enjoyable; they can maintain the artist’s legacy and contribute to life. Artists without these three elements of skill, style and vision are prospects for fifteen minutes of fame. Fifteen minutes of fame results when great things are achieved in a short period of time, and the fifteen minutes represent a moment of recognition of the great vision that the artist has displayed, even though he has not enough skill to create again or to carry out his vision for a longer time.</blockquote>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>5. Artists today are creating and leading new businesses like never before, focusing on the design and art first. How do you think this will improve society, and what troubles should we focus on as artist\'s facing this new world?</strong>\r\n\r\nArtist have lots of power to change and improve life, funny this question too is in the ”Origin of Inspiration” book “Essay Six: Meaningful Purpose. It is about how to have the right purposeful mission in life that is in harmony with nature. In pursuit of 15 minutes fame and attention we formulate a sensational approach to grabbing attention forgetting how complex nature works.\r\n\r\nAfter the 15 minutes expires we realize life goes on.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Author Sam Adoqeui Discusses How to Become a Successful Artist','','publish','closed','closed','','sam-adoqeui','','','2014-04-25 05:15:12','2014-04-25 05:15:12','',0,'http://robertwilliams.wpengine.com/?p=80',0,'post','',0,NULL);
