INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (82,2,'2013-04-04 00:28:09','2013-04-04 00:28:09','','samadoqeui','','inherit','open','closed','','samadoqeui','','','2013-04-04 00:28:09','2013-04-04 00:28:09','',80,'http://robertwilliams.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/samadoqeui.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0,NULL);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (84,2,'2013-04-04 00:47:21','2013-04-04 00:47:21','I discuss one of the most underrated apps for hiring designers with founder Sacha Greif. How he got Folyo off the ground, and his process for ensuring successful web projects.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<strong>1. When first starting folyo, how did you get designers to want to sign up, and people with projects to want to post there?</strong>\r\n\r\nTo get designers to sign up, I simply asked them one by one. I used Dribbble to find designers whose worked I really liked, and then contacted them either through their \"Hire Me\" button, or via Twitter. In fact, I did this so much that Dribbble kindly warned me that I was abusing their service… and I stopped right away of course!\r\n\r\nSo I would say I probably got at least 100 out of the 400 designers currently on Folyo by contacting them personally.\r\n\r\nRegarding the projects, it was a little bit harder. I also contacted companies personally one by one, but that didn\'t prove too successful. In the end, the most effective way has been contacting incubators like YCombinator or 500Startups to ask them to let their startups know about Folyo.\r\n\r\nOf course, the other most common way I got (and still get) projects for Folyo was simply referring clients that contact me personally as a designer. I\'m lucky enough to get 1-2 project inquiries a week, and that was enough to kickstart Folyo in the beginning.\r\n\r\n<strong>2. What\'s the lowest price you would charge, personally, on an awesome logo design project or web design project?</strong>\r\n\r\nI don\'t really work like this, because I bill by the hour. But I can tell you the lowest I would bill is $150/hour, and it\'s also the highest. I don\'t believe in negotiating: I either work at my full rate, or for free (or in exchange for a service). I believe any compromise just devalues your work and leaves everybody unhappy (well, ok, the client will be happy, so basically it just sucks for you!).\r\n\r\n<strong>3. How do you advertise folyo currently? How has it changed / what have you learned from first starting out?</strong>\r\n\r\nI don\'t advertise Folyo, at least in the classic sense of paying for ads. I guess what has changed is that I\'ve given up, in a way. In the beginning I was ready to follow the classic startup gameplan of buying traffic via ads, getting featured on TechCrunch, having a movie made about me (or is that just for Facebook?), etc.\r\n\r\nBut I soon realized that this wasn\'t going to work for Folyo. First of all I run Folyo by myself, so I can\'t move as fast as a 2 or 3-man startup. But more importantly, Folyo itself is different from most startups: I\'m going for quality over quantity, and growth for growth\'s sake would be pointless.\r\n\r\nSince Folyo\'s promise is to put you in touch with reliable designers, the brand itself has to be reliable before people will trust it. So now, instead of worrying about advertising or traffic, I just try to improve the product step by step and have a more long-term view.\r\n\r\n<strong>4. At what point did you decide to run folyo full-time - and when did you know it was a success?</strong>\r\n\r\nTo be honest, I\'m still not running Folyo full-time, and I sure wouldn\'t call it a success.\r\n\r\nThe reason I\'m not running it full-time is simply because I like doing other stuff, like working on side projects, blogging, or thinking up my next big idea. That doesn\'t mean I\'m not committed to Folyo, just that I\'m doing things a little bit differently from most startups. For example, I can go for a week or two without touching Folyo\'s codebase at all.\r\n\r\nAnd I wouldn\'t call it a success because it\'s not capable of supporting me financially by itself just yet. Of course when I say it\'s \"not a success\" it means that I haven\'t met all my goals yet, not that I think it\'s a failure!\r\n\r\n<strong>5. What made folyo different from other ideas you\'ve had? How will you use the experience of creating a successful internet service into future projects?</strong>\r\n\r\nOne year ago, just before launching Folyo, I had another idea, Talkbee (you can see a landing page here: http://talkbee.heroku.com). The idea was simple: Talkbee was a marketplace to sell short consulting sessions via Skype or chat, about anything you\'d like. Design, programming, playing guitar…\r\n\r\nThe difference between Talkbee and Folyo and the reason I chose to go with Folyo in the end is that unlike Talkbee, Folyo had an obvious market (which I was relatively familiar with) and path to revenue.\r\n\r\nThis is obviously the biggest problem with most startups: they don\'t make money. Not that I\'m complaining about apps like Path or Instagram being free, but I knew that I didn\'t want to take in any outside investment so I looked for an idea that could conceivably pay my rent one day.\r\n\r\n<strong>6. What are the differences between selling a service (folyo) and selling a product (ebook)? Which one would you recommend for people with no experience in either?</strong>\r\n\r\nSelling a service like Folyo requires a lot more infrastructure and effort than selling a product like an eBook or icon set. Then again, selling wordpress themes (a product) also requires a ton of effort and support (which almost makes it a service, when you think about it).\r\n\r\nSo it\'s hard to say. Both have their pros and cons. Folyo is also a special kind of service, as it doesn\'t have recurring billing (which is usually the biggest advantage by far of building a service vs a product). So it\'s probably not the best example… but if you can build a service where people pay you every month and you can roughly know how much money you\'ll be making in advance, then that\'s obviously the best possible outcome for you.','Sacha Greif Discusses Tactics behind His First App Launch','','publish','closed','closed','','sacha-greif','','','2014-04-25 04:58:21','2014-04-25 04:58:21','',0,'http://robertwilliams.wpengine.com/?p=84',0,'post','',0,NULL);
