INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (114,2,'2013-04-15 23:05:14','2013-04-15 23:05:14','<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-88\" alt=\"sacha-greif\" src=\"http://robertwilliams.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/sacha-greif.png\" width=\"590\" height=\"233\" />\r\nI discuss one of the most underrated apps for hiring designers with founder Sacha Greif. How he got Folyo off the ground, and his process for ensuring successful web projects.\r\n<!--more-->\r\n[note]<strong>This post was originally sent to my mailing list. </strong>Sign up to get exclusive content before anyone else by <a href=\"http://www.startupdesignnewsletter.com\">clicking here</a>.[/note]\r\n\r\n<strong>Usually I\'m against giving your customers too many choices.</strong>\r\n\r\nI’m sure there are some of you out there that don’t watch football.\r\n\r\nAlthough, I’m also sure that every one of you are familiar with the NFL as a brand. For me,  growing up with an NFL-junkie dad - meant I grew to appreciate it from an early age.\r\n\r\nAs you know the NFL is insanely popular.\r\n\r\nWhat you may not realize is some of the subtle but brilliant design &amp; branding cues that have made the sport insanely popular - which can be applied by almost any company on earth.\r\n\r\nOne of the inaugural acts of becoming a fan of the NFL is choosing a favorite team. Like buying a car, the act of choosing a favorite team was pretty exciting.\r\n\r\nGrowing up, it wasn’t a decision of whether I would choose a favorite team, it was a decision of which favorite team I should choose.\r\n\r\n<strong>Most people assume the actual games are the product NFL is selling, and that is wrong. What they’re actually selling is an experience of having a favorite team. </strong>\r\n\r\nThe choice isn’t should I like football, it’s which football team do I like?\r\n\r\nHow did the NFL accomplish this?\r\n\r\nThink about your startup, are users choosing between products or are they deciding whether they will even buy one of your products.\r\n\r\nIf you could make that one change, how much revenue would it mean to your business?\r\n\r\nThe NFL’s brand is one of the most valuable in the world. That’s because they approach each product (which again is the experience of having a favorite team) with an extreme amount of detail and passion.\r\n\r\nThinking back, that’s what gets us excited about football. Especially children (aka prospective nfl fans) watching at home, they’re attracted to the bright colors.\r\n\r\nThe shiny bright paint on each team’s helmet, the carefully crafted logos for each team, the sleek looking uniforms, the freshly painted fields, and the colors that their parents are dressed in as they watch the game.\r\n\r\n<em>All are perfectly crafted and maintained to make you feel a part of something.</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>The NFL is able to pull this off because it approaches branding products like a craftsman.</strong>\r\n\r\nThis is where startups can take a page from their book. You can and should approach the branding your products in the same way --- even if you only have one product.\r\n\r\nYou need to make the experience of becoming a customer of yours not about whether or not they should join, but about which part of your company is their favorite.\r\n\r\nIt’s not going to look like the NFL, you’re not going to offer a different version of your product for different cities--- but you are going to give each product (or portion of a product) a unique experience that separates it from the rest.\r\n\r\nMake people who value that feature most feel like you care about their particular experience by giving them something unique and visually satisfying.\r\n\r\n<em>Can startups actually do this?</em>\r\n\r\nActually, a few startups are already doing this. For example, teamtreehouse.com is a training course for learning web design and development.\r\n\r\nAt first glance their site may look like a normal well-designed brand. However, when we dive deeper we see some of the same visual branding cues the NFL uses at play.\r\n\r\nThey have branded each individual course with a separate icon depicting that course. Further, check out the badge system they’ve introduced below- where people who successfully finish a course get a special icon making them feel like part of an exclusive team.\r\n\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/SJIcObTsWWh1FmHpoTDQleBOcCXIQmppdWGPmAp9sTSRp9QDz_PEPd8vR_VAiQAXLl7ig0jPBgaqL2nuAqDZi7HYGIDtVfuolSB0tRbo9-tqEynyKcsucFo\" />\r\n\r\nOften, we don’t make the decision of choosing between our products a sexy and fun process - when in reality that process is an integral part of selling our product to them - which is an integral part of our business.\r\n\r\nEven showing off our products, we treat like a sterile, boring act by giving users generic pricing tables, or raw data, and overall a similar experience across all customers.\r\n\r\nVery few startups give each product any type of individualism, instead just listing features, leaving the user to separate each one.\r\n\r\nThink about how you sell your product or products. Compare it to Treehouse who only has one product, and yet they present it in a way so it feels like there is something for everyone.\r\n\r\nEach individual course has a style, and each individual lesson has a badge, and each difficulty level has a different icon. This makes you excited for each one because it creates a sense of individuality.\r\n\r\nAs an example look at the picture below.<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/IMsb15kLy-3Rf_SXKkl5NRl98lEIwtc9955enU80hyEVp255uoBA6nZCg30OeHxTRgoTJv0nO5QnYjhpRsp157c8ScblOAodaCy91Rj2NNYqCsleTNt9HKo\" />\r\nDoesn’t each one of these look like a vastly different and important step?\r\n\r\nIf you were to compare it side by side with no icons or individual branding and only wording to rely on - then they will look like essentially the same class.\r\n\r\n<strong>Someone looking at only the text would think there is no advantage to taking one or the other. </strong>\r\n\r\nThis is where design can step in and create, a better experience. Such a better experience in fact, that it will separate your startup’s product from the others.\r\n\r\nIt can change your customers decision from ‘should I choose this startup or startup x’ to ‘which of this company’s products is my favorite.’ That, is a powerful change.\r\n\r\nSincerely,\r\nRobert\r\n\r\n<em>PS. We’ll get them next year, go niners!</em>\r\n\r\nPSS. W<em>ant some free ideas about how you can do this for your specific startup? Reply to this email and let’s discuss it.</em>\r\n[note]<strong>This post was originally sent to my mailing list. </strong>Sign up to get exclusive content before anyone else by <a href=\"http://www.startupdesignnewsletter.com\">clicking here</a>.[/note]','Why you should steal the NFL\'s best branding tactic...','','draft','open','closed','','nfl','','','2014-04-25 04:56:47','2014-04-25 04:56:47','',0,'http://robertwilliams.wpengine.com/?p=114',0,'post','',0,NULL);
