ng which time I witnessed his tremendous growth and development. I have extensive first hand experience with his ability as a designer. He has impressed me with his concepts and his passion for design. During that time, I have grown to know and respect Rob for his commitment to unique design and a balanced approach to the concepts and execution. He is open to critical comments, is open to new ideas and takes direction very well. His ideas are always presented professionally and persuasively. \r\n\r\nHe also has a good attitude and works well with others. He is a student with excellent work habits. He is successful in improving his skills, and he works hard to do so. Rob is a student that is efficient in planning projects, punctual in meeting deadlines, and conscientiously adheres to company standards and guidelines. \r\n\r\nHe is smart, dedicated, passionate and was a pleasure to have him as a student. Any company would benefit from having him on their team.\"\r\n\r\n<strong>Mike Savacool - Co-Founder - Savacool Secviar</strong>\r\n\"Robert Williams consistently helped my design agency with his through, compelling, engaging, craftsman-quality design. His work is up to our client\'s high standards and having his contributions has proven to be a good value for our studio. Using Robert\'s talent and experience to supplement our internal team has been a great investment.\"\r\n\r\n<strong>Steve Secviar - Co-Founder - Savacool Secviar </strong>\r\n\"Robert has a great ability to digest the bigger picture and trickle it down to the smallest facet of the project at hand. Mix that with a great personality, great design sense and an entrepreneurial mind set and you\'ve got a great asset. I would recommend Robert to anyone who values attention to detail and critical thinking.\"\r\n\r\n<strong>Adlen Afane - Founder</strong>\r\n\"Thanks to the newsletters, I now know exactly how to work with freelance designers and guarantee I get the highest quality from any project. This will pay huge dividends to my company for all future design projects.\"\r\n\r\n<strong>Pierre Nouaille-Degorce - Founder - Speak Native French</strong>\r\n\"Having my startups web-design reviewed by Robert made an immediate impact on my conversion rate. Because of the insight I acquired I\'ve been able to quickly optimize my website\'s design. I didn\'t have the time to become a great designer, so having it all laid out for me was a huge help.\"\r\n\r\n<strong>Dr. Patricia Billings DDS - Founder</strong>\r\n\"Robert created a beautiful custom website, tailored to my goals and he was a pleasure to work with.\"\r\n</div>','Testimonials','','publish','open','closed','','testimonials','','','2013-07-01 03:05:16','2013-07-01 03:05:16','',0,'http://robertwilliams.wpengine.com/?page_id=157',0,'page','',0,NULL);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (162,2,'2013-07-07 06:24:16','2013-07-07 06:24:16','Freelance businesses, like most businesses, waste time.\r\n\r\nWhether you\'re spending hours on twitter, or building a pixel-perfect website -- there is a ton of time we spend \"working,\" which yields little to no results for our actual business.\r\n\r\nThis isn\'t always a bad use of our time necessarily, but still, how many times have you felt drained at the end of the day and ended up going to sleep without really being able to recall what you got done? I\'m very much guilty of this myself.\r\n\r\nIn fact, I\'ve designed over a dozen personal portfolios for myself.\r\n\r\nAnd in school, I thought it was critical that I update my portfolio every quarter. I\'d stay up late, refining every aspect, and killing myself to get it done along the way.\r\n\r\nLittle did I know that only a few years after graduating, deleting my portfolio and focusing on my communication (specifically the emails I write) to potential clients would be the key to helping me go from $20/hr to over $150/hr.\r\n\r\nBut it wasn\'t only in college. Just yesterday, in fact, I spent most of my day wasting time by thinking about how to redesign my current site.\r\n\r\n<strong>So why do I say this time is wasted?</strong>\r\n\r\nAs you may know, about a month ago I created a survey (called: Designers talk money) which included responses from over 120+ freelance designers and marketers.\r\n\r\nThe results are astounding. Any freelancer, OR small business for that matter, will be able to take away some really awesome insights from the data.\r\n\r\nI\'ve highlighted just a few the key takeaways that stood out to me.\r\n\r\n<span class=\"highlight\">- The average freelancer makes $3,430 per month</span>\r\n<span class=\"highlight\">- The average freelancer gets 2.46 leads from their website per month</span>\r\n<span class=\"highlight\">- 61% of freelance projects come from referrals</span>\r\n<span class=\"highlight\">- The average freelancer hourly rate is about $29/hr</span>\r\n\r\nNow, these numbers may be right and they may be wrong, but that doesn\'t matter because the real value and insight comes when you start to compare these numbers relatively to what freelancers said they do when they have no clients.\r\n\r\nFor example:\r\n\r\n<span class=\"highlight\">- People who email prospects and leads directly when they are out of work make on average $5,515, compared to $2,316 for people who say they do nothing or wait for work to come to them. </span>\r\n\r\n<strong>What does this mean?</strong>\r\n\r\nIt means freelancers who do not wait for clients to come to them, on average make twice as much money. It\'s the difference of a $30k per year salary and a $66k per year salary! Also known as twice as much money!\r\n\r\nHowever, despite this data, an overwhelming majority (64% of everyone surveyed) say they either do nothing or just network generally (or on social media) to find work.\r\n\r\nIt makes sense right? You don\'t want to be over bearing, or too salesy, so we instead go with a passive approach - post to twitter, or our blog, update our website.\r\n\r\nBut why?\r\n\r\nNetworking generally (while by far the most popular tactic) was actually the second lowest earning tactic...\r\n\r\n-- and according to my survey less then two-and-a-half leads come from your website per month. Most of which you probably don\'t close, so at best you can get about one client every few months from your site.\r\n\r\n(Unless you do some serious optimizing... for that checkout: <a href=\"http://doubleyourfreelancingrate.com/the-blueprint\">Brennan Dunn\'s the Blueprint</a>)\r\n\r\nIs it really working to perfectly polish your portfolio and have to constantly update it?\r\n\r\nWhy not try going for the most effective way?\r\n\r\nOptimize the biggest, most effective part of your freelance business, instead of worry about the tiny details.\r\n\r\nFor example if roughly 60% percent of your projects come from referrals (like the freelancers I surveyed) why not try to focus on getting even more referrals?\r\n\r\n<strong>Here\'s how I do it: </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><!--more--></strong>\r\n\r\nWhen I\'m coming close to the end of a project, I\'ll simply send an email like this:\r\n\r\n<em>\"Oh and by the way, I\'m thinking of doing a case study about *ProjectName* on my website, with your permission? I would also love to include a testimonial from you about my work with :CompanyName: - something like this would be perfect: </em>\r\n\r\n\"Buying Robert\'s design services to create a website that is measurably adept at getting more customers is a guaranteed investment.\r\n\r\n:ClientName: - Founder\"\r\n\r\nIn fact, if you\'re busy at the moment, I can use that quote for now. Either way, let me know, thank you!\"\r\n\r\nThis works for me 99% of the time, because all a busy client has to say is \"yea sure\" and bam, the work is done.\r\n\r\n(BTW, this is the same way I approach all of my emails to clients during the project as well. I do all the work for my client, and just give them options or a yes or no question they can choose between.)\r\n\r\nAfter all, my job is to do this project FOR my client - and to lay everything out for them perfectly in order to minimize their time commitment. NOT give them more work by having to manage me.\r\n\r\nOnce I get a testimonial (which is basically a referral to the whole world), I\'ll go in and ask directly for a referral.\r\n\r\n<em>\"Hey :ClientName:, Thanks for the testimonial this was an awesome project. </em>\r\n\r\nI’d like to continue working with you - I have a few ideas for what we can do in the next few weeks to add to this project and make it even more successful.\r\n\r\nI’ll send those over soon, but for now if you know of anyone who would beneﬁt from a similar service, I would love it if you could send me their email and I’ll let them know that you were thinking this might be right for them, and answer any questions they have about how your project worked out (I\'ll CC you on the email)!\r\n\r\nSound good?\"\r\n\r\n<strong>Again, that approach takes all the hard-work away, by doing it for the client. They simply email you who they have in mind, and you will take care of the rest.</strong>\r\n\r\nDoes this seem too easy, like it\'s a little wrong? Well, that\'s because I designed it to be easy.\r\n\r\nI\'ve tested these \"scripts\", and I have dozens more I use for all kinds of things.\r\n\r\nI\'ve spent about a year refining them and making sure they\'re written to get results. I\'ve taken them from online courses, blog posts, bootcamps, and then molded them, and made them my own.\r\n\r\nI actually use them to provide MORE value to my clients while making sure I\'m focusing on things that are truly important to my business.\r\n\r\nThe truth is, that\'s what clients pay me to do - write copy and design strategies that gets them huge results (either in more revenue or saving time) --- so I\'ve just applied the same copywriting service to my own business internally.\r\n\r\nIt\'s helped me a lot. If you\'re interested, or have any scripts you use that you\'d like to share with me please reply to this blog post.','Optimizing Your Time as a Freelancer (Surprising Survey Results)','','publish','closed','closed','','freelance-time-waste','','','2014-04-25 05:18:08','2014-04-25 05:18:08','',0,'http://robertwilliams.wpengine.com/?p=162',0,'post','',0,NULL);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (163,2,'2013-07-07 06:23:02','2013-07-07 06:23:02','','emails-freelance','','inherit','open','closed','','emails-freelance','','','2013-07-07 06:23:02','2013-07-07 06:23:02','',162,'http://robertwilliams.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/emails-freelance.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0,NULL);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (165,2,'2013-07-18 06:05:42','2013-07-18 06:05:42','When you’re shopping for a product, you’re in one of two modes. <em>A) Shark mode:</em> you know what you want and your on a mission to find it and buy it as quickly as possible… or <em>B) Browse mode:</em> you’re taking your time learning and shopping for the best product or the best deal.\r\n\r\nEither way, you’re going to have to interact with a website to find a product. Nothing is as important on a site with lots of products as its navigation design – it’s also one of the most poorly designed features.\r\n\r\nIn most cases that safe and generic nav bar on your website’s awesome wordpress or magento theme you picked out, is probably not that great at selling your product.\r\n\r\nAfter all, most random eCommerce sites you see on the web have completely different navigation systems. Sometimes they’re great – and other times finding what you’re looking for is like pulling teeth.\r\n\r\nYou can scour a site for a few minutes and literally feel so disgusted with the layout and infrastructure of the site that you’ll literally refuse to deal with the company, and in fact pay more to someone else if their site is easier to use (like… your competitor?). It simply makes you feel like your shopping somewhere that doesn’t care about it’s customers, and doesn’t care what the experience of shopping on their store is like.\r\n\r\n<strong>You can\'t afford confusing your customers with bad navigation.</strong>\r\n\r\nNobody cares about your low prices if you have a navigation that is infuriating to use or is so poorly designed that it looks unprofessional.\r\n\r\nSo, what’s the remedy for this extremely difficult problem? Great design. But what if you don’t have tons of money to spend to figure out how customers love to shop? Don’t worry…\r\n\r\nThat\'s why you should look at how the World’s Best Ecommerce sites have studied, designed, and developed their world-class navigation best practices.\r\n\r\nA handful of billion dollar companies have already cracked the code and you must simply observe and mimic (pronounced: steal) their designs in order to benefit.\r\n\r\nWhy start from scratch if you can start from world-class?\r\n\r\nLook at the worlds best and apply their million dollar solutions to your website (usually this just equals applying a little common sense to your site).\r\n\r\nKnowing that companies like Amazon, Apple, Target and a few others spend millions of dollars on putting together the most well-thought-out &amp; easy to use navigations, here’s some of the solutions they’ve come up with, and use to avoid the 3 revenue killer navigation mistakes you\'re probably making:\r\n\r\n<strong>1. The Product Heavy Solution that caters to both shopping modes: sharks and browsers... Case Study: Amazon</strong>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-169\" alt=\"amazon1\" src=\"http://robw.co/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/amazon1.png\" width=\"600\" height=\"385\" />\r\n\r\nIf you want to buy a book where are you going to go? Amazon. In fact, if you want to buy a lot of things you’re most likely going straight to them. This has made them one of the biggest sites in the world, and it wouldn’t be possible without great design.\r\n\r\nTheir redesigns, particularly in their navigation, have been highly talked about for good reason – they sell products like nobody’s business.\r\n\r\nWith so many products, and so many different categories, they’ve seemingly settled on a vertical solution for choosing categories on the homepage. Interestingly, when you hover over each category a more exciting image of a featured product appears, enticing you to choose that category.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-170\" alt=\"amazon2\" src=\"http://robw.co/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/amazon2.png\" width=\"600\" height=\"385\" />\r\n\r\nThe psychology here is remarkable. One may argue that the categories section is their secondary navigation system behind their search bar – and they’d be correct. However, what’s more important is how each shopper (remember shark mode vs. browse mode?) is presented information. If you know what you want, you will likely not even see the categories and go straight to the search unencumbered.\r\n\r\nHowever, if you just want to look around – Amazon begins the custom tailored selling process with beautiful featured images for each category.\r\n\r\n<strong>Copycats: Walmart and Ebay</strong>\r\n\r\nWalmart has a similar, but less sophisticated audience… reflects their homepage solution perfectly. The site uses the same vertical category layout, except with less elegance and sizzle. Instead we see a more straight-forward take of listing categories and sub-categories in pretty simple text link format.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-171\" alt=\"walmart\" src=\"http://robw.co/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/walmart.png\" width=\"600\" height=\"385\" />\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-176\" alt=\"ebay3\" src=\"http://robw.co/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/ebay3.png\" width=\"600\" height=\"385\" />\r\n\r\nMaybe you should copy Walmart and Ebay and copy Amazon?\r\n\r\n<strong>2. The High-end store solution that highlights every inch of sizzle on their product... Case study: Apple</strong>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-172\" alt=\"apple\" src=\"http://robw.co/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/apple.png\" width=\"600\" height=\"385\" />\r\n\r\nApple can sell. They, contrary from Amazon, only have a few products. They also make twice as much profit as Amazon... which makes you wonder how they can sell such high-end (some would even say overpriced) products so effectively? The power of design and marketing.\r\n\r\nApple basically creates an amazing unique landing page for each of its products. It\'s hard to find the buy button on any of these pages because Apple is so focused on presenting and selling every last inch of it\'s products. These type of landing pages are what tons of startups could benefit from.\r\n\r\nIf you want to learn how to write copy for these types of pages, <a href=\"http://robw.co/warning-startups-need-good-copy-more-then-design/\">checkout my blog post on writing effective copy.</a>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-173\" alt=\"apple2\" src=\"http://robw.co/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/apple2.png\" width=\"600\" height=\"385\" />\r\n\r\nHowever, before the customer ever sees any of this, they first encounter a pretty standard nav bar. What’s not so standard, however, is the meticulous nature in which the categories, and sub-categories have been organized.\r\n\r\nInstead of separating it’s products with common phrases like say computer, phones, tablets (as seen on most other sites like Samsung) – they have the amazing apple brand-speak refer to it’s products.\r\n\r\nIt may seem like no other company in the world could do this, however that’s totally false. Sure — no one else can create a category called “the iPhone”, but any company can speak to their customers using their own words and terminology that change the experience from \"shopping for a phone\" to \"shopping for their phone\".\r\n\r\n<strong>3. The easy to narrow down between similar products when searching solution... Case Study: Google</strong>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-174\" alt=\"google\" src=\"http://robw.co/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/google.png\" width=\"600\" height=\"385\" />\r\n\r\nI don\'t think Google created this design for sorting your product search results, but they\'ve definitely perfected it.\r\n\r\nIt makes sense that a company whose entire service is basically connecting people to information via search focuses entirely on search when it comes to their shopping platform; Google Shopping.\r\n\r\nConsidering the fact that Google isn’t exactly an eCommerce website, they focus solely on connecting you with information and presenting it clearly and intuitively. Still this is a very interesting case study for eCommerce sites, especially those who utilize a search feature heavily.\r\n\r\n<strong>Copycat: Everyone</strong>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-177\" alt=\"amazon3\" src=\"http://robw.co/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/amazon3.png\" width=\"600\" height=\"385\" />\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-178\" alt=\"ebay\" src=\"http://robw.co/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/ebay.png\" width=\"600\" height=\"385\" />\r\n\r\nObviously, Google Shopping features a very common left sidebar solution which is great for narrowing down specific features you’re looking for within a search with tons of products. It\'s not unique in that Ebay, Amazon, and tons of other sites use the exact same sidebar layout, but it is effective. The fact that all of these billion dollar companies have used and continue to use this feature tells me it’s the most effective way of narrow down what products people are searching for.\r\n\r\n<strong>Applying these principles to your site:</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>1. The High-end Solution</strong>\r\n\r\nIf you sell fine jewelry, instead of having a category in your navigation called “rings,” try something that features a unique selling point that only you can offer like, \"Rebecca\'s Hand-chosen Ring Collection\".\r\n\r\n<strong>2. The Product Heavy Solution</strong>\r\n\r\nGive the sharks a clear search bar, but also cater to the browsers by offering a secondary navigation that allows them to enjoy the shopping experience a little more. Consider landing pages specifically designed to sell high-end or top-selling products, ala Apple.\r\n\r\n<strong>3. The Search Solution</strong>\r\n\r\nPut yourself in the users shoes and ask yourself what information would someone need in order to pick between two similar products. Then go in and ad a sorting feature that caters to that criteria in the search results.','How people find products everyday, navigation designs you should steal...','','draft','closed','closed','','ecommerce-navigation','','\nhttp://robw.co/warning-startups-need-good-copy-more-then-design/','2014-04-25 04:56:14','2014-04-25 04:56:14','',0,'http://robertwilliams.wpengine.com/?p=165',0,'post','',0,NULL);
