INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (220,2,'2013-10-18 22:04:01','2013-10-18 22:04:01','I graduated in June 2011.\r\n\r\nI remember my favorite professor asking me, “Rob, where do you wanna to work?”\r\n<h3>Having spent that semester researching agency’s, I dreamed of working at a Google-esque workplace at million dollar ad agency and doing award-winning work on world-famous clients.</h3>\r\nAnd still, it felt like a dumb question to me. Where do I want to work?\r\n\r\nI had just gone to Art School for 3 years, full of financial aid pricks, art snobs, and private school bureaucrats — so as far as I was concerned: I didn’t give a crap. Any agency, any design job, would be fucking awesome. I’d get paid to listen to music and design stuff, and that’s awesome.\r\n\r\nEven more awesome though, was landing an internship just a few days later. I went in, they liked my work — and gave me a job the week after my graduation, done and done.\r\n\r\nThe agency was in a cool old brick building — it was downtown (a cool western old town type of scene, with great food).\r\n\r\nThe inside of the place was dark, and all the furniture, desks and conference room were vintage wood and rad.\r\n\r\nWhen it came to working with this group —I had a blast. We’d goof off a little bit, watch youtube videos, have a few beers after work, but the coolest part was how everyone seemed to love what they did and respect the work we produced.\r\n\r\nIt was a fun time.\r\n\r\nUntil it wasn’t. At first I didn’t mind doing intern grunt work, after all I was happy to have a real job in the industry. While others I graduated with were flipping burgers or working at best buy, I was becoming a great designer, learning from industry leading professionals (and now, friends) — but that only lasted so long.\r\n<h3>I began to see that I was losing control of my future.<!--more--></h3>\r\nHow much I was paid, the projects worked on, and most other important factors of my career and life, were completely out of my control.\r\n\r\nI worked my ass off for that agency for 6 months. I thought that by doing more work than anyone else I\'d prove my value. Initially, the design agency said they\'d consider bringing me in after 3 months... then 6 months.\r\n\r\nThen I got a job offer… from another company. It was an in-house job that wasn’t going to be nearly as fun, and I knew it. But it had benefits, and the “stability” of a salary (42k per year).\r\n\r\nI thought it was a perfect time to ask the design agency for a full-time position. Here’s how the conversation went:\r\n\r\n“Robert, we know we said we’d discuss bringing you in full-time once you\'d been here for 6 months, but we’d like to extend you another offer. Bust your ass for us for another 6 months and we can talk about a full-time position.”\r\n\r\n“I got a job offer, I’m going to take it if I don\'t get some sort of offer from you guys.”\r\n\r\n“...”\r\n\r\nSo that was that.\r\n\r\nI took a crappy job with the “stability” of a salary. It was the logical progression for me at that point in my career.\r\n\r\nA few months passed, and although I wasn\'t learning or having as much fun, it went ok.\r\n\r\nIn the most soul-crushing and life demoralizing sort of way you can possibly mean \"it went ok.\"\r\n\r\nSo when I <a href=\"../deleted-my-portfolio/\">got fired</a> when new management was brought in. It was a relief.\r\n\r\nAt that point I made one of the best decisions ever. I began freelancing full-time. Soon I was making more money in half the time.\r\n\r\nBeyond the money, it had other huge advantages.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>I got to decide what I worked on.</li>\r\n	<li>I set my own price, and gave myself raises.</li>\r\n	<li>My reputation began to grow online.</li>\r\n	<li>The process I followed when designing was my own, I could try new things and experiment.</li>\r\n	<li>I was in control of my future.</li>\r\n	<li>And <strong>I made more money.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIt was eye-opening to see what kind of freedom is possible if you take it.\r\n\r\nThen my former professor came to me again. He asked me if I wanted to interview with two big agencies.\r\n\r\nI did.\r\n\r\nThey both said the job was mine if I wanted it.\r\n\r\nI’d be working on awesome projects, with some of the best talent in the world. Everything I had dreamed of when I graduated.\r\n\r\nI turned them down.\r\n\r\nWhat’s the point of finding a dream job? Is it stability? Is a situation where you can be fired at any point really that stable? Is it learning from world-class talent? Does learning from people in one agency really beat <a href=\"../mentors/\">learning from people all around the world online</a>.\r\n\r\nSome say, \"But you gotta bust your ass in order to make it.\" Why? Fuck busting my ass. When you have zero control over your future and how quickly you progress, is it really worth it to bust your ass? Is working 60-70 hr weeks ever a good thing — even if you’re a freshly graduated creative that hasn’t paid their dues?\r\n\r\nIt\'s much easier to bust my ass now, knowing that I\'ll reap the rewards from my business.\r\n\r\n<strong>Anyways, I mute every ad I come across - why on earth would I want to work for an ad agency? Remote working is the future, I\'m just already there.</strong>\r\n\r\nWhen those two agencies came knocking I had only been out of school for less then two years. Sure, my portfolio looked good, but it was something else entirely that attracted them to me.\r\n\r\nI could tell you, but I\'d like to hear what you think that is?\r\n\r\nSincerely,\r\nRobert Williams','Why I Turned down 2 Dream Jobs 12 Months after Graduating','','publish','closed','closed','','turned-down','','','2014-04-25 05:12:43','2014-04-25 05:12:43','',0,'http://robertwilliams.wpengine.com/?p=220',0,'post','',0,NULL);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (221,2,'2013-10-18 22:06:26','2013-10-18 22:06:26','Through the years I\'ve learned from many. The internet has brought on a huge advantage to the individual. The ability to decide what information they want to take in from the largest collection of information ever assembled. Some of these people know I look at them as mentors, others do not but they\'ve all had a large impact on how I think and do.\r\n<h2>My mentors: (in no order)</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/The-Revolution-Manifesto-Ron-Paul/dp/0446537527/ref=pd_sim_b_4\">Ron Paul</a>, I\'ve followed Dr. Paul\'s ideas and principles since his 2008 presidential campaign. Tons of wisdom about economics, liberty, and government.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://sandiegoportfolio.com\">Henry Hikima</a>, I was Henry\'s student in college, and since he\'s helped me land interview after interview.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://copyhackers.com\">Joanne Weibe</a>, I\'ve read her books on copywriting and have taken courses on writing emails and conversion optimization.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://37signals.com/rework/\">David Heinemeier Hansson and Jason Fried</a>, I\'ve based a lot of my business on the princples in \"Rework\", and have studied their writing on business and staying small.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://doubleyourfreelancingrates.com\">Brennan Dunn</a>, I\'ve more then doubled my freelancing rate thanks to his teachings and techniques. He\'s a person who has provided me and my business a ton of value for free.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://30x500.com\">Amy Hoy</a>, I\'ve learned how to build products from her; \"30x500\" and it\'s completely counter-intuitive approach.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://sachagreif.com\">Sacha Greif</a>, I\'m a heavy user of Sacha\'s \"folyo.me\" for helping connect great designers with great startups, I\'ve also learned a lot about design from him.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://howsuccessfulartistsstudy.com\">Sam Adoqeui</a>, I based my learning\'s in college on his books \"Origin of Inspiration\", and \"How successful artists study.\" Two great books for artists.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://iwillteachyoutoberich.com\">Ramit Sethi</a>, I took Ramit\'s course\'s; \"Earn1k\" and \"Success Triggers\"; on starting a business and improving lifestyle. I strongly recommend his book \"I will teach you to be rich.</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://kalzumeus.com\">Patrick Mckenzie</a>, I completely changed how I value my work from one his blog posts, and have continued to follow his continued advice ever since.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>I send free actionable emails to online businesses and freelancers about improving their business every week.</h3>\r\nIt\'s a small but active mailing list so I can get personal about real problems, and I think you will get tons of value from it. Members also also get access to premium things I put together periodically, no spam or b.s.\r\n\r\n<form action=\"http://robw.createsend.com/t/i/s/nkhjr/\" method=\"post\"><input id=\"fieldName\" type=\"text\" name=\"cm-name\" placeholder=\"Your name\" />\r\n<input id=\"fieldEmail\" type=\"email\" name=\"cm-nkhjr-nkhjr\" placeholder=\"Email\" required=\"\" />\r\n<button type=\"submit\">Subscribe</button></form>','Business Mentors','','publish','closed','closed','','mentors','','','2014-04-25 03:25:04','2014-04-25 03:25:04','',0,'http://robertwilliams.wpengine.com/?page_id=221',0,'page','',0,NULL);
