INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (250,2,'2013-11-07 18:00:20','2013-11-07 18:00:20','<section>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\nLast week, I listened to a <a href=\"http://productpeople.tv\">Product People</a> podcast that inspired immediate action. It was an interview with Ruben Gamez of Bidsketch. The one part I remember distinctively is him saying, \"Ya there\'s a lot of people listening to podcasts but not a lot of people taking action as a result\". One week later I had <a href=\"http://letsworkshop.com/?utm_source=how-i-created-passive-income&amp;utm_medium=blogarticle&amp;utm_campaign=inline-text-click\">a paid product</a> and over $300/month in monthly recurring revenue.\r\n<h3>I had a deep pain in my business.</h3>\r\nMy freelance business is prone to dry spells. Most are, and I know that because everywhere I go online people are complaining about this. Next, they usually ask what the best place to look for work is, and someone responds with a link to a job board.\r\n\r\nJob boards are designed for people looking for a full-time job. These people can stop looking once they find that position. Freelancers, on the other hand, need to be perpetually searching job boards in order to get value from them, even when they’re already fully-loaded with billable hours — because they know the next project is right around the corner. This adds yet another thing to worry about and makes using job boards a never-ending exhaustive chore for a busy freelancer.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>That pain didn\'t have an adequate solution.</h3>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\nThat’s why there are so many dry spells in the average freelancer’s business. How can you scour through thousands of job postings every day when you’re up to your nose in client work (that you\'re being paid to do)?\r\n\r\nSo what do most freelancers end up doing? We group all of our job searching to when we don’t have any paid work. When we’re looking for work our job searching output goes to a million. Once we get a project, and knock it out of the park, it’s time to scramble for work again.\r\n\r\nThere’s something inherently wrong with this formula. Not only for the freelancer but also for the people looking to find freelancers on job boards.\r\n\r\nWhy shouldn’t the job poster have access to the best person for their job, regardless of if they check the job board that day? If you check job boards once a month, the person who posted that awesome project 15 days ago never had access to your skill and expertise.\r\n\r\nThe thing about it is, freelancers don’t realize the true issue. Everywhere I go they’re asking about where to search for freelance leads — and asking for tips on how to find work. A lot of them probably use a batching approach, only searching for work once every few weeks (if they’re lucky) and using an RSS reader to view all leads in one place.\r\n\r\nThat approach is a little better, but still not quite right because it doesn’t answer the question of replying to the right job boards at the right time (as quickly as possible).\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>I had intimate experience with these crappy \"fixes\".</h3>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\nLike I said, I’m a freelancer myself. I’ve been freelancing for the past 3 years, and while this doesn’t make me an expert, I’ve gone from making $0 to charging $2,900+/week. Along the way, I’ve replied to job boards, and I’ve joined private freelancer communities, and I’ve networked.And like most freelancers I’ve posted on dribbble, twitter, and all the other designer social network places in hopes of “getting my name out there.”\r\n\r\nThe same problem always persists. When I’m on a project, all of that stuff goes out the window for paying work.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->I can’t even spend 1-2 hours a day searching for leads when I’m in the middle of a project.\r\n\r\nAnd I’ve tried outsourcing. I’ve hired a personal assistant, and spent weeks trying to train them. I’ve even gotten my girlfriend to reply to job leads for me.\r\n\r\nHowever, no one can pitch my business as well as I can. No one will know the right wording to use when talking about my business and what I do. Even when I write a script for contacting leads (and I’ve done it) I’m still not 100% satisfied.\r\n\r\nMore importantly, unless the person that is contacting leads for you is a high-paid freelance designer, they’re probably not going to know which leads are worth contacting.\r\n\r\nSo you’re left in the same same position of having to do it all yourself.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>I turned the daily task of solving this pain for my business into a paid product.</h3>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\nI decided that I, as a freelancer, didn\'t want to leave my email in order to reply to a job post. Job boards only exist to find the lead. Usually most of the on-boarding and negotiation happens via email, skype or something else — so why do we as freelancers need job boards at all?\r\n\r\nTo find the work right? Well, this week I started a new service. I spend 3-5 hours every single day and come up with the best freelance jobs of the day from all over the web. I painstakingly hand-craft this list every day. I choose them based on a few criteria;\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>They have to be freelance leads.</li>\r\n	<li>They need to be remote, and open to freelancer’s anywhere.</li>\r\n	<li>They have to be quality projects (ideally leading to $10k+ opportunities and nothing below $1k).</li>\r\n	<li>And ideally, there needs to be an email and name attached to the lead.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nI then send these leads to a private list of freelancers. Basically, I\'m only sending the leads I would actually contact for myself. Only the leads that are 100% worth their time. The rest? I discard them, so they never have to waste time searching through crap again.\r\n\r\nNow, I think this service is worth $3,000/month to any freelance design business. In other words, I believe it would generate that much extra revenue for any company, if all that was done was reply to these leads everyday.\r\n\r\nBut I launched the service at only $34/month.\r\n\r\nKeeping the list small will mean raising this price very soon. Right now, with little promotion, only a handful of people have signed up and they’re receiving tons of value. Not only reaching more leads per day, but also saving tons of time freed up in the process.\r\n<blockquote>Look, I\'ll give my testimonial for the site: \"shut up take my money\".\r\n\r\n— Jonathan Courtney (@Jicecream) <a href=\"http://robertwilliams.createsend1.com/t/i-l-ajruyk-l-r/\" target=\"_blank\">November 3, 2013</a></blockquote>\r\n<blockquote>I joined this week and have gotten three days of emails. I\'ve responded to four leads. Saves me huge time.\r\n\r\n— Kurt Elster (@kurtinc) <a href=\"http://robertwilliams.createsend1.com/t/i-l-ajruyk-l-y/\" target=\"_blank\">October 31, 2013</a></blockquote>\r\n<blockquote>It\'s handcrafted, definitely worth a shot.\r\n\r\n— Robin Raszka (@robinraszka) <a href=\"http://robertwilliams.createsend1.com/t/i-l-ajruyk-l-j/\" target=\"_blank\">October 31, 2013</a></blockquote>\r\n<h2>I also am completely over-delivering value to my customers.</h2>\r\nThink about this. Basic math says if a freelancer is charging $100/hour and they spend 1/hr per month looking for leads online, they\'re already spending about 3x what I’m charging for this service.\r\n\r\n<strong>They\'re also only seeing 1/100th of the 1200 leads that I am sending to my subscribers.</strong>\r\n\r\nIf that weren’t enough, I\'m letting people signup for this service 100% risk-free. If at any point they don’t feel the leads they get are worth the money they paid, they can cancel and get a full refund for that month. Anyone can try it out for an entire month.\r\n\r\nAny smart freelancer will see the value in this. If they land even one $1k+ project, it will pay for their subscription for two and a half years. Why not try it out for a month and see if it’s worth it?\r\n\r\n<strong>Today, a little more than a week in, I sent my first workshop-exclusive lead, meaning the lead is not from a job board but from a lead that contacted me directly and is only being sent out to my subscribers. A project for close to $1k only being sent out to about ten people. How\'s that for value?</strong>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://letsworkshop.com/?utm_source=how-i-created-passive-income&amp;utm_medium=blogarticle&amp;utm_campaign=inline-text-click\">Join workshop now and get today\'s leads!</a>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</section>','How I Created Passive Income in Less than a Week, by over Delivering Value','','publish','closed','closed','','how-i-created-passive-income','','','2014-04-25 05:17:06','2014-04-25 05:17:06','',0,'http://letsworkshop.com/blog/?p=250',0,'post','',0,NULL);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (254,2,'2013-11-27 09:02:52','2013-11-27 09:02:52','<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-255\" alt=\"danielmall\" src=\"http://letsworkshop.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/danielmall.jpg\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1065\" />\r\n\r\n<em>Daniel Mall runs an awesome studio called <a href=\"http://superfriend.ly/\">Superfriendly</a>. They have great work and awesome clients. What I like more about his approach is he teaches everything he knows to other freelancers, <a href=\"Dan Mall interview What is something you think freelancers are doing wrong when looking for work? The truth is, it’s tough for everybody. I have the same problems as any other freelancer or design business. Sometimes you’re just like “where is everybody?” Freelancing is feast or famine in nature. Sometimes that doesn’t change. That said, good lead generation — and even retaining clients is—all about positioning. You have to get specific about what you do and how you’re better than the average freelancer online. A lot of freelance designers aren’t doing that and that contributes to why they can’t land more work. How many leads should a designer contact before landing a project?  It’s less about how many you contact as it is about being proactive about finding work. Most of my clients find me through my website, so I really need my website. Some designers don’t even have a website. Contacting people works, and most freelancers simply won’t do it. You need to go out and find the work not just let it come to you.  I’ve never had a paying client come in through Dribbble, and that’s because on Dribbble I’m competing with thousands of the world’s best designers.  On the other hand, when they come to me through an acquaintance or my website, I’ve presented myself totally different. I get to sell myself on my terms and show potential clients exactly what I’m world-class at. Doing that makes it becomes less about comparing me to others and more about how I’m special and passionate about the work I specialize in. What are barriers you\'ve had moving up the value chain of freelancing?  Saying no to cash is tough to this day— but it comes back to one thing; knowing what you do far better than everybody else, and having the guts to do it and sell it. It’s risky, because if you want to do a particular type of work, that means you have to turn work down. It means you have to say no—and it’s hard to say no when you’re in a position where you are depending on the money coming in. Saying no to cash is always hard. It doesn’t get easier, because there’s always going to be something that will push you to do work simply for that next paycheck — whether it’s paying employees or being late on your rent. How do you go from pitching 5k-10k projects to pitching 100k+ projects? How do you find them? What changes in strategy and approach need to happen in order to 10x your rate?  It’s not about pitching different types of projects. It’s about you, your rate, and your confidence. That said you can’t go from pitching a $2,000 project to pitching a $200,000 in a day — there’s simply too much that has to happen in between.  Like I said you have to focus on the one thing that you do better than anyone else. Realize that your network is one of the most powerful things you have, and if you look on linkedin or facebook you can probably find people that work at places you would consider “dream projects.” People that are already in your network.  The fact is you’re more likely to pitch a 200k project to one of your current clients or someone in your network. Improve what you offer to your current clients, then you can charge more. Try making a list of dream clients and see who you know that works there, you will be surprised how big of a network you already have.  Once you find your niche, your world gets a lot smaller for the better. You compete for the same projects with the same competitors and soon you have a close group of people you can go to for work, and advice.\">via the articles on his blog</a> and in person. I had a chance to discuss some of the most important  topics for freelancers last week and his answers were insanely valuable to my freelance business.</em>\r\n\r\n<strong> What is something you think freelancers are doing wrong when looking for work?</strong>\r\n\r\nThe truth is, it’s tough for everybody. I have the same problems as any other freelancer or design business. Sometimes you’re just like <em>“where is everybody?”</em> Freelancing is feast or famine in nature. Sometimes that doesn’t change. That said, good lead generation — and even retaining clients is—all about positioning. You have to get specific about what you do and how you’re better than the average freelancer online. A lot of freelance designers aren’t doing that and that contributes to why they can’t land more work.\r\n<strong></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>How many leads should a designer contact before landing a project?</strong>\r\n\r\nIt’s less about how many you contact as it is about being proactive about finding work. Most of my clients find me through my website, so I really need my website. Some designers don’t even have a website. Contacting people works, and most freelancers simply won’t do it. You need to go out and find the work not just let it come to you.\r\n<h1>\"I’ve never had a paying client come in through Dribbble, and that’s because on Dribbble I’m competing with thousands of the world’s best designers.\"</h1>\r\nOn the other hand, when they come to me through an acquaintance or my website, I’ve presented myself totally different. I get to sell myself on my terms and show potential clients exactly what I’m world-class at. Doing that makes it becomes less about comparing me to others and more about how I’m special and passionate about the work I specialize in.\r\n\r\n<strong>What are barriers you\'ve had moving up the value chain of freelancing?</strong>\r\n\r\nSaying no to cash is tough to this day— but it comes back to one thing; knowing what you do far better than everybody else, and having the guts to do it and sell it. It’s risky, because if you want to do a particular type of work, that means you have to turn work down. It means you have to say no—and it’s hard to say no when you’re in a position where you are depending on the money coming in. Saying no to cash is always hard. It doesn’t get easier, because there’s always going to be something that will push you to do work simply for that next paycheck — whether it’s paying employees or being late on your rent.\r\n\r\n<strong>How do you go from pitching 5k-10k projects to pitching 100k+ projects? How do you find them? What changes in strategy and approach need to happen in order to 10x your rate?</strong>\r\n\r\nIt’s not about pitching different types of projects. It’s about you, your rate, and your confidence. That said you can’t go from pitching a $2,000 project to pitching a $200,000 in a day — there’s simply too much that has to happen in between.\r\n\r\nLike I said you have to focus on the one thing that you do better than anyone else. Realize that your network is one of the most powerful things you have, and if you look on linkedin or facebook you can probably find people that work at places you would consider “dream projects.” People that are already in your network.\r\n\r\nThe fact is you’re more likely to pitch a 200k project to one of your current clients or someone in your network. Improve what you offer to your current clients, then you can charge more. Try making a list of dream clients and see who you know that works there, you will be surprised how big of a network you already have.\r\n\r\nOnce you find your niche, your world gets a lot smaller for the better. You compete for the same projects with the same competitors and soon you have a close group of people you can go to for work, and advice.','Daniel Mall Discusses Going from $10k Projects to $100k','','publish','closed','closed','','daniel-mall','','','2014-04-2