INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (267,2,'2013-12-18 04:17:30','2013-12-18 04:17:30','<a href=\"http://youtu.be/6rrq1WX6lLE\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-269\" alt=\"Nick Disabato is #1 \" src=\"http://letsworkshop.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Screen-Shot-2013-12-17-at-4.56.56-PM.png\" width=\"658\" height=\"404\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Last week I did a live interview with my friend Nick Disabato </strong>exclusively for <a href=\"http://letsworkshop.com/\">Workshop</a> members.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Nick is a great guy who has tons of experience working with a variety of clients and optimizing his freelance business. He sends an awesome </span><a style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\" href=\"http://nickd.org/\" target=\"_blank\">newsletter about interaction design and freelancing</a><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">. He crowd-funded </span><a style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\" href=\"http://cadence.cc/\" target=\"_blank\">a book on interaction design</a><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">... which is an awesome compilation of evergreen principles to product design (that he picked up from client work).</span>\r\n\r\n<strong>And probably the coolest thing he\'s done is productize his consulting services</strong> - which in the process creates a large, EXTREMELY STEADY source of income for his business. Check out his awesome landing page for his product: <a href=\"http://draft.nu/revise/\" target=\"_blank\">draft revise.</a>\r\n\r\nIf you can\'t tell, he was a great guy to talk to about how to level up a freelance business.\r\n\r\nHe reached out to me because he was interested in joining workshop - and I invited him to join us for a live interview. He also stuck around for a campfire Q+A, so watch the video then check out his answers to some great member questions.\r\n\r\n<strong>Nick\'s template for new inquiries:</strong>\r\n\r\n\r\n<blockquote>___________,\r\n\r\nHi! Thanks so much for thinking of me for this project. I\'d love to chat and see if I\'d be a good fit for you.\r\n\r\nI have a few questions that I tend to ask everyone before we get on the phone, so I can learn your business better and understand your needs:\r\n\r\n– Why are you looking to start this project? And what business goals do you have in mind after it\'s successfully executed?\r\n\r\n– What\'s the total budget that you have for this?\r\n\r\n– Do you have an internal team that might put this together, or should I work to assemble one that can help me out?\r\n\r\n– When are you looking to get started?\r\n\r\n– Are you the leader of this project? And should we plan on inviting anyone else to the initial consultation?</blockquote>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<strong>Campfire questions:</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Q: How do you typically respond to leads that are online like Workshop? A boilerplate cover letter?</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Nick:</strong> I try to find the name of someone there that might be receiving the email, address them directly and discuss something they are working on. You want to make the email about solving *their* needs, not introducing yourself and talking about how great you are.\r\n\r\n<strong>Q: Any tips for bypassing the typical NDAs and using case studies, etc., to highlight past client work in your portfolio?</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Nick:</strong> I tend to make this a huge part of my client negotiations. I almost never sign NDAs, unless they are very, very lax and generally phrased as non-competes or confidentiality agreements. Getting case studies and telling the world about my work is how I am able to build my reputation.\r\n\r\nOne probable result of this: I end up working for smaller businesses. I will *never* sign an NDA as a precondition of talking with clients. Lots of startups want me to do that because they think their idea is too valuable. 1) It isn\'t; 2) I take maybe like 5 meetings a week, and NDAs would never scale. Try to explain this to people – probably like 80% of them continue to have the meeting anyway, and the other 20% go away. Those 20% I would never want to work with in the first place.\r\n\r\n<strong>Q: Would you say that a social media presence should drive people to your site and not vice versa?</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Nick:</strong> Social media is a good way to stay present and available in the industry. I would say a mailing list should be used along with social media as well. That said, your website is your home turf, and the way the internet works, nobody can take it from you. Consider social media an away game ^_^\r\n<div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n<strong>Q: We\'ve talked about cold emailing potential prospects and how one should structure those emails (with Robert referencing his <a href=\"http://www.bidsketch.com/blog/sales/cold-email/\">great article on Bidsketch</a>), but how would that apply to an existing posting from a job board you might get from something like Workshop? </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Would you use the same template for new inquiries if you\'re the one emailing the client first, rather than them finding you?</strong>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n<strong>Nick:</strong> Workshop is culling many posts from job boards… those clients may not have heard of workshop. You may want to preface your email with \"I saw your post on the 37signals\' job board, but it was culled as an especially good option on workshop. I work with the best clients, and…\"\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n<strong>Robert: </strong>On most of the leads I send I try to include a link to their website in addition to the job posting. This will give you somewhere to start digging for background info, so you can tie your service back to them and what you find interesting about their project.  This is another way to do as Nick says and preface your email with something personal.\r\n<div>\r\n<div><strong>Nick:</strong> One really good way that you can get my own attention: do the research on what I like and mention it in your initial outreach. For example;  \"I\'ll treat you to a bottle of rochefort 10 if you\'re ever in seattle,\" is a near-guaranteed way to get a response from me every single dang time.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<h3>Special thanks to Nick Disabato! The next Freelancer interview will be open to anyone, so if you\'re interested - <a href=\"http://robwco.github.io/home/\">signup for my newsletter</a>.</h3>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>','Nick Disabato Shares His Secrets to Building a Productized Consulting Service','','publish','closed','closed','','nickd','','','2014-04-25 05:10:19','2014-04-25 05:10:19','',0,'http://letsworkshop.com/blog/?p=267',0,'post','',0,NULL);
