INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (286,2,'2014-02-20 00:06:50','2014-02-20 00:06:50','I think the key to improving a freelancer\'s sales funnel is identifying the different steps involved in the sales process. It\'s funny, but I don\'t think I\'ve ever heard a freelancer talk about this all that much.\r\n\r\nFiguring out the different steps involved in selling your service allows you to easily see where clients are dropping off, and what you need to improve. Every freelancer has a different process when it comes to work, but almost every project starts the exact same way:\r\n\r\n<b>1.) Pre-inquiry:</b>\r\nIt begins with a client or freelancer finding one another. For us, a lot of our leads are coming in through <a href=\"http://letsworkshop.com/\">Workshop</a> - but the clients don\'t know that. Alternatively, (and hopefully often) a client will hit us up from our website or online profile. There\'s also referrals, which happen serendipitously.\r\n\r\n<b>2.) Initial contact or inquiry about project:</b>\r\nNext, an email or phone call is made expressing interest in working together. Typically, this is a pretty short and simple correspondence, involving the exchange of contact info and sharing a little background on the project and the freelance\'s availability and specialization. The hope is to identify an initial fit and connect again in the future.\r\n\r\nNote: Some clients want a ballpark price range off the bat at this stage, and may ask to see more work from the freelancer related to their project. In order to provide a price range, the freelancer will usually respond by asking a few specific questions about the project, which leads to the next step.\r\n\r\n<b>3.) Inquiry Review: </b>\r\nThe freelancer and client will each assess whatever information they\'ve been given about working together, if desired they will schedule some sort of follow up meeting.\r\n\r\n<b>4.) Outline or pre-roadmap meeting:</b>\r\nThe freelancer and client meet over skype, telephone call, or in person to discuss the project yet again. Typically, this is where a decision is made... both sides give a rough idea of what they\'re looking for, and receive a solid understanding of what working together will look like.\r\n\r\n<b>5.) Creating an initial roadmap/proposal/scope whatever you call it: </b>\r\nUsually the freelancer then sits down to put together some sort of proposal (preferably with the client there). The kickoff meeting is great for seeing if personalities will match but not for putting ink to paper about what is expected. Often, the client\'s decision about working together has already been made.\r\n\r\n<b>6.) Defining Deliverables and Expected Delivery Dates: </b>\r\nThe client will look at the completed roadmap and possibly ask to refine/change it. This is usually a string of emails, questions, and back-and-forth about the project until most details are ironed out.\r\n\r\n<b>7.) Project Pitch:</b>\r\nThe freelancer will either present or send over a revised proposal. This may include a contract and invoice, at which point the client will either accept, decline, or negotiate a lower rate.\r\n\r\n<b>8.) Research / Positioning / Story Crafting / Copywriting / Design / Development:</b>\r\nThe freelancer begins work on the project, starting by learning as much as possible about the project and company he\'s working with. It involves understanding your customer deeply and getting inside their heads. Once a freelancer has adequately researched the project, he begins creating the deliverables.\r\n\r\nYou\'ve probably never seen it laid out this way. How do your projects start? <a href=\"http://twitter.com/letsworkshop\">@letsworkshop</a>','Every project starts the same','','draft','closed','closed','','every-project','','','2014-04-25 04:43:46','2014-04-25 04:43:46','',0,'http://letsworkshop.com/blog/?p=286',0,'post','',0,NULL);
